#Project

The nature of the project we are proposing to undertake is analyzing voter turnout rates in jails for populations that are incarcerated before their trial. Therefore, they have not been convicted of a crime and are still eligible to vote in elections. The goal is to highlight the lack of accessibility and awareness for voter registration, i.e., being asked if they would like to register to vote, actually obtaining an absentee ballot, etc.

Background

This project relates to representation in the political system of individuals that are incarcerated before trial but have not yet been convicted of a crime. This misrepresentation disproportionately affects lower income individuals and individuals of color, because poor people cannot afford bail and people of color are more likely to be given higher bails. This relates to feminist principles, because there is a huge imbalance in power of representation within our government. It is estimated that there are about 750,000 individuals in the United States that are incarcerated and awaiting trial. This can make a huge difference in who is and who is not elected to government. Further, the individuals that are elected have the capability to create reforms to our wildly biased criminal justice system. As stated before, the ones most affected by pre-trial bail are the ones who are least represented in our political system and are often overlooked or disproportionately targeted by our society. This project is important, because it will bring awareness to the lack of accessibility to voting for people that are incarcerated while awaiting trial. Awareness is the first step to making proactive changes to our society, and exposing the poor rates of voting within these systems will hopefully create a space for individuals to create voting centers, proactively give absentee ballots, etc. to these communities.

VDR Dataset

Our dataset comes from the Houston Justice organizations campaign called Project Orange, which works to increase voter registration for prison inmates and their families. It consists of data from 3 separate days in September 2018 during which VDRs from Harris county went to Harris County Jail to register people to vote.

Methods

After obtaining the dataset, we used R to complete our further analysis. We began by cleaning the dataset to contain only relevant information for our question. After this we created graphs to determine the percent of accepted applications of the total amount registered and the voter turnout. Upon receiving the dataset, we found that it was lacking demographic information regarding the populations that were registered to vote. To combat this we used information from the Harris County Jail Website to interpret the overall jail population demographic and apply it to the dataset.

Voter Turnout & Sums Dataset

Import data

VoterTurnoutData <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/prernaadvani/QTM-490-Final-Project/master/VoterTurnoutData_1.csv")

Clean

#Clean
names(VoterTurnoutData)[names(VoterTurnoutData) == "Number.of.Registered.Voters"] <- "NumRegister"
names(VoterTurnoutData)[names(VoterTurnoutData) == "Number.of.Applications.Received"] <- "NumApp"
names(VoterTurnoutData)[names(VoterTurnoutData) == "Not.Valid.to.Register"] <- "InvalidApp"
names(VoterTurnoutData)[names(VoterTurnoutData) == "Voter.Turnout"] <- "VoterTurnout"

VoterTurnoutData_1 <- select(VoterTurnoutData, "NumRegister", "NumApp", "InvalidApp", "VoterTurnout", "Date") %>% 
  na.omit(VoterTurnoutData_1)
VoterTurnoutData_1

Application Accepted Data

#Graph for accepted applications
VoterTurnoutData_2 <- melt(VoterTurnoutData_1, id.var=c("Date", "VoterTurnout", "NumApp"))
ggplot(data=VoterTurnoutData_2, aes(x=Date, y=value, fill = variable, color = variable)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") + labs(title = "Accepted and Rejected Applications Per Weekend in Harris County Jail")

#Graph for rejected applications
VoterTurnoutData_3 <- VoterTurnoutData_1 %>%
  group_by(Date) %>%
  mutate(AppRejectedPercent = InvalidApp / NumApp)

ggplot(data=VoterTurnoutData_3, aes(x=Date, y=AppRejectedPercent)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="blue") +
  labs(title = "Rejected Registration Applications Per Weekend in Harris County Jail")

Voter Turnout Data

#Voter turnout graph
VoterTurnoutData_4 <- VoterTurnoutData_1 %>%
  mutate(NumNotVote = NumRegister - VoterTurnout) 
VoterTurnoutData_5 <- melt(VoterTurnoutData_4, id.var=c("Date", "InvalidApp", "NumApp", "NumRegister"))
ggplot(data=VoterTurnoutData_5, aes(x=Date, y=value, fill = variable, color = variable)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") + labs(title = "Voter Turnout Per Weekend of Registration in Harris County Jail")

#Voter turnout graph
VoterTurnoutData_6 <- VoterTurnoutData_1 %>%
  group_by(Date) %>%
  mutate(VoterTurnoutPercent = VoterTurnout / NumRegister)

ggplot(data=VoterTurnoutData_6, aes(x=Date, y=VoterTurnoutPercent)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", fill="blue") +
  labs(title = "Voter Turnout Percent Per Weekend of Registration in Harris County Jail")

Statistical Analysis

Interpretation

Preliminary data indicates that there were a large number of voter registration applications that were rejected. Weekend 1, 104 applications were rejected, while Weekend 2 and 3 had 53 and 125 applications respectively. Compared to the total number of applications, Weekend 1 had a rejection rate of 35.49%. Weekend 2 had a rejection rate of 35.57%, and weekend 3 had a rejection rate of 23.27%. The weighted overall rejection rate was then 28.80%. For actual voter turnout, for the Weekend 1 group had a turnout of 35 applications or a rate of 18.51%, while Weekends 2 and 3 had turnouts of 21 and 180 respectively, making their turnout rates 21.85% and 43.68%. Thus, the weighted overall turnout was 33.85%. This data is limited to one non-profit that registers voters in one jail. Thus, we must contextualize the data. This can be done in a couple of different ways. First, we must look at the total number of voters within the jail to see how many people were registered (or attempted to be registered) compared to the whole. Further, we must compare this data to data for other individuals that are not incarcerated (i.e.comparing data to the rest of the state). Additionally, this project can be extended to include other counties, metros and states. Although Project Orange specifically looked at Harris County, the next step for this project would be to collect data on rates of voting restrictions for people held in pre-trial incarceration in other counties within the Houston area. After keeping a running datasheet from the Houston metroplex, it could then be expanded to other major cities like Dallas and Austin, then to Texas, and then other states in the US. This could be done using a similar method of sending VDRs to the county jails and register inmates to vote.
